sentence-detokenized: EU rejects German call for a boycott of British lamb.
Peter Blackburn
BRUSSELS 1996-08-22
The European Commission on Thursday disagreed with German advice that consumers should avoid British lamb until scientists determine whether mad cow disease can be transmitted to sheep.

Germany's representative on the European Union's veterinary committee, Werner Zwingmann, said on Wednesday that consumers should buy sheepmeat from countries other than Britain until scientific advice is clearer.
"We do not support any such recommendation because we see no reason to do so," Commission chief spokesman Nikolaus van der Pas told a press conference.
He said that more scientific studies are needed and, if action is found to be necessary, the EU should act.

According to him, the proposal put forward last month by EU Agriculture Commissioner Franz Fischler to ban sheep brains, spleens and spinal cords from the human and animal food chains is a very specific and preventive measure to protect human health.

Fischler proposed EU-wide measures following reports from Britain and France indicating that, under laboratory conditions, sheep could contract bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE), the mad cow disease.

But Fischler agreed to revise his proposal after the EU's standing veterinary committee, the national animal health officials, questioned whether such action was justified, as there was only a slight risk to human health.
Spanish Agriculture Minister Loyola de Palacio had earlier accused Fischler, at a meeting of EU agriculture ministers, of provoking unjustified alarm by making "dangerous generalisations".
Only France and Britain supported Fischler's proposal.
EU veterinary and multidisciplinary scientific committees are due to re-examine the issue early next month and make recommendations to senior veterinary officials.
Sheep have long been known to contract scrapie, a brain-deadening disease similar to BSE, which is thought to be transmitted to cattle through feed containing animal waste.

British farmers denied Thursday that their sheep pose a danger to human health, but expressed concern that the German government's advice to consumers to avoid British lamb could influence consumers across Europe.
"What we need to be very mindful of is how other countries are going to follow Germany's example," National Farmers' Union of Wales (NFU) president John Lloyd Jones told BBC radio.

Bonn has led efforts to protect public health after consumer confidence plummeted in March following a British report suggesting that humans could contract mad cow disease from eating contaminated beef.
Germany imported 47,600 sheep from Britain last year, almost half of total imports.
4,275 tonnes of British lamb meat have been introduced, 10% of total imports.
A rare draft of a Hendrix song sells for nearly $17,000.
A rare handwritten draft of a song by legendary American guitarist Jimi Hendrix sold for nearly $17,000 on Thursday at an auction of some of the late musician's favourite possessions.
A Florida restaurant paid £10,925 ($16,935) for the draft of "Ain't No Telling", which Hendrix wrote on a London hotel stationery in late 1966.
At the end of a January 1967 concert in the English city of Nottingham, he threw the sheet of paper into the audience, where it was retrieved by a fan.
Buyers also snapped up 16 other items that were put up for auction by Hendrix's ex-girlfriend Kathy Etchingham, who lived with him from 1966 to 1969.
Among them was a black lacquer and mother-of-pearl inlaid box used by Hendrix to store his drugs, which an anonymous Australian buyer purchased for £5,060 ($7,845).
The guitarist died of a drug overdose in 1970, aged 27.
China says Taiwan spoils the atmosphere of the talks.
BEIJING 1996-08-22
China on Thursday accused Taipei of spoiling the atmosphere for the resumption of cross-strait talks with a visit to Ukraine by Taiwanese Vice President Lien Chan this week that infuriated Beijing.

Within hours after Chinese state media said the time had come for political talks with Taiwan, Foreign Ministry spokesman Shen Guofang told Reuters: "The atmosphere necessary for the opening of talks has been disturbed by the Taiwanese authorities".
State media quoted China's chief negotiator with Taipei, Tang Shubei, as telling a group of visitors from Taiwan on Wednesday that it was time for the rivals to hold political talks.
"Now is the time for the two sides to engage in political talks....
which is to end the state of hostility," Tang was quoted as saying in Thursday's edition of the overseas edition of the People's Daily.

Shen, of the Foreign Ministry, told Reuters Television in an interview that he had read reports of Tang's comments, but did not elaborate on why the negotiator felt the time was right for talks with Taiwan, which Beijing considers a renegade province.
China, which has long opposed all Taipei's efforts to gain greater international recognition, was angered by Taiwanese Vice President Lien's visit to Ukraine this week.
China says the time is right for talks with Taiwan.
BEIJING 1996-08-22
China has said that it is time for political talks with Taiwan and that the rival island must take practical steps towards that goal.

The official Xinhua news agency quoted Tang Shubei, executive vice president of the Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Strait, as saying that consultations should be held to establish the timing and format of the talks.
Car registrations in Germany in July are up 14.2 percent year-on-year.
FRANKFURT 1996-08-22
First registrations of motor vehicles in Germany rose by 14.2% in July this year compared to the previous period, the Federal Motor Vehicle Office reported on Thursday.
The bureau said 356,725 new cars were registered in July 1996: 304,850 passenger cars and 15,613 trucks.
The figures represent an increase of 13.6% for passenger cars and a decrease of 2.2% for trucks compared to July 1995.
Motorbike registrations increased by 32.7% in this period.
The growth was partly due to an increase in the number of Germans buying German cars abroad, while manufacturers said domestic demand was weak, the federal office said.
Almost all German car manufacturers recorded increases in registrations in this period.
Volkswagen AG achieved 77,719 registrations, just over a quarter of the total.
Opel AG, together with General Motors, came in second place with 49,269 registrations, 16.4% of the total figure.
Third was Ford, with 35,563 registrations, up 11.7%.
Only Seat and Porsche had fewer registrations in July 1996 compared to July last year.
Seat registered 3,420 registrations, compared to 5,522 in July of the previous year.
Porsche registrations fell to 554 from 643.

Israel plays down fears of war with Syria.
Colleen Siegel
JERUSALEM 1996-08-22
Israel's outgoing peace negotiator with Syria said Thursday that current tensions between the two countries appear to be a storm in a teacup.
Itamar Rabinovich, who as Israel's ambassador to Washington conducted unsuccessful negotiations with Syria, told Israel Radio that it seemed Damascus wanted to talk rather than fight.
"It seems to me that the {(1)[MISC] Syrian priority} remains to negotiate.
The Syrians are confused, they are definitely tense, but the general assessment here in Washington is that this is essentially a storm in a teacup," he said.
Rabinovich is ending his term as ambassador.
He will be replaced by Eliahu Ben-Elissar, Israel's former envoy to Egypt and a right-wing Likud party politician.
On Wednesday, Israel sent a message to Syria via Washington that it was committed to peace and wanted to start negotiations without preconditions.
But he criticised Damascus for creating what he called a dangerous atmosphere.
Syria on Wednesday accused Israel of launching a hysterical campaign against it after Israeli television reported that Damascus had recently test-launched a missile.
He said his arms purchases were for defensive purposes.

"The message we are sending to (Syrian President Hafez al-) Assad is that Israel is ready at any time, without preconditions, to enter into peace negotiations," Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy told Israel Radio in an interview.
Tensions have risen since Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu took office in June vowing to retain the Golan Heights, which Israel captured from Syria in the 1967 Middle East war.
Israeli-Syrian peace talks have been stalled over the Golan since 1991, despite the previous government's willingness to make concessions on the Golan.
Peace talks between the two sides were last held in February.
"The voices coming out of Damascus are bad, not good.
The media...
are full of expressions and statements that must be worrisome....
This artificial atmosphere is very dangerous because those who spread it can become its prisoners," Levy said.
"We expect Syria, if its face is that of peace, to respond to Israel's message to enter into peace negotiations because that is our goal," he said. "
We don't want a war, God forbid.
No one benefits from wars. "
Israeli Channel Two television said Damascus had sent a "signal of calm" to Israel.
He did not give a source for the report.
Spokesmen for Netanyahu and Levy said they could not confirm this.
The television also said Netanyahu had sent messages to reassure Syria via Cairo, the United States and Moscow.
A Polish diplomat denies that nurses are stranded in Libya.
A Polish diplomat on Thursday denied a report in a Polish tabloid this week that Libya was denying exit visas to 100 Polish nurses trying to return home after working in the North African country.
"This is not true.

As of today, we are not aware of any nurses stranded or held in Libya without their will, and we have not received any complaints," Tadeusz Awdankiewicz, chargé d'affaires at the Polish embassy in Tripoli, told Reuters by telephone.

Poland's labour ministry said this week it would send a team to Libya to investigate, but Awdankiewicz said the investigation was prompted by some nurses complaining about their working conditions, such as non-payment of wages.
He said there are an estimated 800 Polish nurses working in Libya.
Two Iranian opposition leaders meet in Baghdad.
Hassan Hafidh
BAGHDAD 1996-08-22
An Iranian exile group based in Iraq vowed Thursday to extend support to Iran's Kurdish rebels after they were attacked by Iranian troops deep inside Iraq last month.

A Mujahideen Khalq statement said its leader, Massoud Rajavi, met with the secretary general of the Kurdistan Democratic Party of Iran (KDPI), Hassan Rastegar, in Baghdad on Wednesday and expressed his support for the rebel Kurds in Iran.
"Rajavi stressed that the Iranian Resistance would continue to stand by his fellow Kurds and the resistance movement in Iranian Kurdistan," he said.
A spokesman for the group said the meeting "signals a new level of cooperation between Mujahideen Khalq and Iranian Kurdish opponents".
Iran intensively bombed targets in northern Iraq in July in pursuit of KDPI fighters based in Iraqi Kurdish areas outside the control of the Baghdad government.
Iraqi Kurdish areas bordering Iran are under the control of the Patriotic Union of Iraqi Kurdistan (PUK) guerrilla group.
The PUK and the Iraqi Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP), the two main Iraqi Kurdish factions, have had control of northern Iraq since Iraqi forces were driven out of Kuwait in the 1991 Gulf War.
Fighting between the two sides erupted over the weekend in the heaviest fighting since last year's US-sponsored ceasefire.
Mujahideen Khalq said Iranian troops had also shelled KDP positions in the Qasri region of Suleimaniya province, near the Iranian border, over the past two days.
He said about 100 Iraqi Kurds were killed or wounded in the attack.
Both Iran and Turkey launch air and ground attacks against targets in northern Iraq in pursuit of their own Kurdish rebels.
A US-led air force in southern Turkey protects Iraqi Kurds from possible attacks by Baghdad's troops.
Saudi riyal rates remain stable in the quiet summer trade.
The Saudi riyal spot against the dollar and riyal interbank deposit rates were mostly stable this week in quiet summer trade, according to traders in the kingdom.
"There was no change in Saudi riyal rates.
The market was very quiet because of the summer holidays," said one trader.
The spot riyal stood at 3.7504 / 06 to the dollar.
One-month interbank deposits stood at 5-1/2, 3/8 per cent, three-month at 5-5/8, 1/2 per cent and six-month at 5-3/4, 5/8 per cent.
One-year funds were at six, 5-7/8 per cent.
Israel approves Arafat's flight to the West Bank.
JERUSALEM 1996-08-22
Israel on Thursday gave Palestinian President Yasser Arafat permission to fly over its territory into the West Bank, ending a brief crisis between Israel and the PLO, an adviser to Arafat said.
"The problem is over.
The president's plane has received permission to pass through Israeli airspace, but the president is not expected to travel to the West Bank before Monday," Nabil Abu Rdainah told Reuters.

Arafat was scheduled to meet former Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres in the West Bank city of Ramallah on Thursday, but the venue was changed to Gaza after Israel denied the Palestinian leader's helicopters flight clearance.
Palestinian officials accused right-wing Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of trying to stop the Ramallah meeting by keeping Arafat on the ground.
Subsequently, Arafat cancelled a meeting between Israeli and PLO officials on civilian affairs at the Allenby Bridge crossing between Jordan and the West Bank.
Abu Rdainah said Arafat had decided not to fly to the West Bank on Thursday, after Israel lifted the ban, because he had a busy schedule in Gaza and would not be free until Monday.
Arafat to meet Peres in Gaza after flight ban.
JERUSALEM 1996-08-22

Yasser Arafat will meet Shimon Peres in Gaza on Thursday, after Palestinians said the Palestinian leader was barred by the right-wing Israeli government from flying to the West Bank for talks with the former prime minister.
